2.1 Introduction

Generally, we will need to distinguish between a forecast or predicted value of yt that was made at some previous time period, say, t âˆ’ ğœ, and a
fitted value of yt that has resulted from estimating the parameters in a time series model to historical data. Note that ğœ is the forecast lead time. 

The forecast made at time period t âˆ’ ğœ is denoted by yÌ‚t(t âˆ’ ğœ). There is a lot of interest in the lead âˆ’ 1 forecast, which is the forecast of the observation
in period t, yt, made one period prior, yÌ‚t(t âˆ’ 1). We will denote the fitted value of yt by yÌ‚t.

We will also be interested in analyzing forecast errors. The forecast error that results from a forecast of yt that was made at time period t âˆ’ ğœ is
the lead âˆ’ğ‰ forecast error   et(ğœ) = yt âˆ’ yÌ‚t(t âˆ’ ğœ). (2.1)
For example, the lead âˆ’ 1 forecast error is  et(1) = yt âˆ’ yÌ‚t(t âˆ’ 1).

The difference between the observation yt and the value obtained by fitting a time series model to the data, or a fitted value yÌ‚t defined earlier, is called
a residual, and is denoted by et = yt âˆ’ yÌ‚t. (2.2)

The reason for this careful distinction between forecast errors and residuals is that models usually fit historical data better than they forecast. That is,
the residuals from a model-fitting process will almost always be smaller than the forecast errors that are experienced when that model is used to
forecast future observations.

